{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.4.0"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[],"dockerImageVersionId":31330,"isInternetEnabled":false,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{"_uuid":"051d70d956493feee0c6d64651c6a088724dca2a","_execution_state":"idle","trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"R PROGRAMMING CAT/ASSIGNMENT 1\n\nQ1). Discuss General introduction to R programming language including rules/ regulations in R programming language.\n\nQ2) Explain how to Set working directory in R . \n\n\nQ3). State and explain Why R programming is important in business analytics. (QUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I / CAT 1)\n\nQ4) Discuss different R Data types and different data structures in R giving examples in each case. (THEORY PART \nQUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I/CAT 1)\n\nQ5) Measures of central tendency in R. (QUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I / CAT I )\nMeasures of dispersion in R  Discuss this mainly mathematically: skewness and kurtosis, semi interquartile range. (QUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I / CAT 1)\nPackages used in R.\n\nQ6) Visualization using ggplot and other packages. (QUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I / CAT 1)\n\nQ7) Exploratory data analysis including histograms. (QUESTION  ASSIGNMENT I / CAT 1)\n\nHow to plot several plots in one interface.\n\nQ8) Discuss different Functions in R. (QUESTION 7 ASSIGNMENT I / CAT 1)\n\nQ9) Simple linear regression in R. (QUESTION 4 ASSIGNMENT I/ CAT 1)\n\nQ10)Multiple linear regression in R. (QUESTION 5 ASSIGNMENT I / CAT I)\n\nEnsure you include their interpretations in terms of coefficients and p values.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":" Discuss General introduction to R programming language including rules/ regulations in R programming language.\n * open-source programming language used for statistical computing, data analysis, and visualization.\n * It is designed for data manipulation, statistical modeling, and graphical analysis, using vectors and built-in statistical functions.  ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":" **Explain how to Set working directory in R .**\n This is the default folder where R reads and saves files.\n  ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"\ngetwd() # check the current dir\n\nsetwd(\"path\")  # sets a working dir\n\nmarks<- read.csv(\"filename\")\nmarks","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.735211Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.736942Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.804630Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.768789Z"}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**State and explain Why R programming is important in business analytics.**\n\n* Powerful Statistical Capabilities, R offers a comprehensive suite of statistical techniques built into its core, including linear and nonlinear modeling, classical statistical tests, time-series analysis, classification, and clustering. This robust foundation is why it's the language of choice for academic research and rigorous statistical analysis.\n* Extensive Package Ecosystem A key strength of R is its vast, community-contributed repository, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN). CRAN hosts over 22,000 packages covering almost any analytical task imaginable, from finance to genetics, allowing users to implement cutting-edge methodologies quickly. The tidyverse collection of packages, for example, provides a streamlined and cohesive framework for data manipulation and visualization.\n* Exceptional Data Visualization R is renowned for its powerful and flexible graphics capabilities, most notably through the ggplot2 package. These tools allow users to create highly customizable, publication-quality plots and interactive web graphics using packages like Shiny.\n* Open-Source and Free As a free, open-source language under the GNU General Public License, R is accessible to everyone, from students to large corporations like Google, Facebook, and the Bank of America, without licensing costs. This open nature fosters a large and active global community that continuously contributes to its development and support.\n* Reproducible Research Tools like R Markdown and Quarto allow analysts to integrate R code, output (like tables and visualizations), and narrative into a single document. This ensures that analyses can be easily replicated and shared, which is vital in academic, scientific, and business reporting.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Discuss different R Data types and different data structures in R giving examples in each case**\n* data type is the classification of data that determines the type of value a variable can store.\n* data structure is a format used to organize and store data efficiently in R.\n* ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"a <- c(1,2,5.3,6,-2,4) \nb <- c(\"one\",\"two\",\"three\") \nc <- c(TRUE,TRUE,TRUE,FALSE,TRUE,FALSE) \nd <- c(4i, 3i)\ne<- c(2L)\nclass(a)\nclass(b)\nclass(c)\nclass(d)\nclass(e)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#VECTOR\nnum_vec <- c(10, 20, 30, 40, 50)\n\nchar_vec <- c(\"Ann\", \"John\", \"Mary\")\n\n\nlength(num_vec)\nlength(char_vec)\nnum_vec[4]\nnum_vec[5]-num_vec[3]","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#matrices\n\nmat <- matrix(1:6, nrow = 2, ncol = 3)\nmat\n\n\nmat[2, 3]\n\n\nmat * 5\n\n\nrowSums(mat)\ncolSums(mat)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#  array\narr <- array(1:10, dim = c(1, 2, 3))\n\n\narr\n\n\narr[1, 2, 1]\n\n\ndim(arr)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#  list\nmy_list <- list(\n  name = \"Ann\",\n  age = 20,\n  scores = c(80, 90, 85),\n  details = data.frame(id = 1:2, dept = c(\"ICT\", \"DSA\"))\n)\n\n\nmy_list\n\n\nmy_list$name\nmy_list$scores\n\n\nmy_list$details$dept","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#  factor\ngender <- factor(c(\"Male\", \"Female\", \"Female\", \"Male\"))\n\ngender\n\n\nlevels(gender)\n\ntable(gender)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#  data frame\ndf <- data.frame(\n  Name = c(\"Ann\", \"Jones\", \"Marynes\"),\n  Age = c(20, 26, 26),\n  Salary = c(37000, 49000, 85000)\n)\n\n\ndf\n\n\ndf$Age\n\n\ndf[1, ]\n\n\nsummary(df)\n\n\nstr(df)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Measures of central tendency in R. Measures of dispersion in R Discuss this mainly mathematically: skewness and kurtosis, semi interquartile range. Packages used in R.**\n\n1.Measures of central tendency are statistics that describe the central or typical value of a dataset\n2.Measures of dispersion describe how spread out data values are from the central value indicating consistency or variability in data\nSkewness is a measure of the asymmetry of a distribution around its mean.\nKurtosis measures the degree of peakedness or flatness of a distribution\nSemi IQR is half of the interquartile range and measures the spread of the middle 50% of data reducing the effects of the outliers\npackages 1.Data Manipulation & Cleaning dplyr: The \"grammar\" of data manipulation (filtering, selecting, mutating). tidyr: For reshaping data and making it \"tidy.\" data.table: High-performance version of data frames for massive datasets. stringr: For cleaning and manipulating text strings. lubridate: For handling dates and times.\nVisualization ggplot2: The industry standard for static, high-quality charts. plotly: For turning static charts into interactive web graphics. lattice: For trellis/multivariate graphics.\nStatistics & Modeling tidymodels: A modern framework for machine learning. caret: The classic toolkit for training and plotting classification/regression models. moments: For skewness and kurtosis. psych: For descriptive statistics and factor analysis. lme4: For linear and non-linear mixed-effects models.\nReporting & Apps shiny: For building interactive web applications directly in R. rmarkdown: For creating dynamic reports, PDFs, and Word docs. knitr: For dynamic report generation and \"knitting\" code with text.\nData Import readr: Fast way to read flat files (CSV, TSV). readxl: For importing Excel spreadsheets. haven: For importing SPSS, Stata, and SAS files. httr: For working with APIs and web data.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"get_mode <- function(x) {\n  freq <- table(x)\n  max_freq <- max(freq)\n  \n  if (max_freq == 1) {\n    return(\"No mode\")\n  }\n  \n  modes <- names(freq)[freq == max(freq)]\n  return(modes)\n}","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"marks <- c(60,56,50,68,48,59,38,58,67,38,56,45,42,32)\nmean(marks)\nmedian(marks)\nvar(marks)\nsd(marks)\nget_mode(marks)","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(moments)\nlibrary(e1071)\nlibrary(psych)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.836236Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:19:56.837739Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.082635Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.080821Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"\nAttaching package: ‘e1071’\n\n\nThe following objects are masked from ‘package:moments’:\n\n    kurtosis, moment, skewness\n\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":4},{"cell_type":"code","source":"marks <- c(60,56,50,68,48,59,38,58,67,38,56,45,42,32)\nskewness(marks)\nkurtosis(marks)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.085354Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.086802Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.107836Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.106222Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"-0.124960101652425","text/markdown":"-0.124960101652425","text/latex":"-0.124960101652425","text/plain":"[1] -0.1249601"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"-1.33076745481258","text/markdown":"-1.33076745481258","text/latex":"-1.33076745481258","text/plain":"[1] -1.330767"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":5},{"cell_type":"code","source":"marks <- c(60,56,50,68,48,59,38,58,67,38,56,45,42,32)\niqr_value <- IQR(marks)\n\n\nsiqr <- iqr_value / 2\n\n\nsiqr","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.110354Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.117362Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.139988Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.138255Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"8","text/markdown":"8","text/latex":"8","text/plain":"[1] 8"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":6},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Visualization using ggplot and other packages.******","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"install.packages(\"ggplot2\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.142497Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:19:57.143880Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:21:01.442318Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:21:01.303340Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"Installing package into ‘/usr/local/lib/R/site-library’\n(as ‘lib’ is unspecified)\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":7},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(ggplot2)","metadata":{"trust