"text/html":"0.0460217562239154","text/markdown":"0.0460217562239154","text/latex":"0.0460217562239154","text/plain":"[1] 0.04602176"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"-1.57561067741123","text/markdown":"-1.57561067741123","text/latex":"-1.57561067741123","text/plain":"[1] -1.575611"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":17},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"* Skewness is positive hence mean> median\n* Kurtosis is greater than the minimum value hence it is platykurtic  showing that extreme  outliers re less frequent ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Write R code that  gives regression model of the effect of age , height and weight on BMI hence write R \ncode that gives the data frame    for the collected data.**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"park <- data.frame(\n  BMI = c(112, 89, 134, 83, 118, 99, 76, 126, 175, 95),\n  Age = c(50, 15, 10, 120, 115, 12, 20, 18, 140, 40),\n  Height = c(7, 5, 3, 8, 4, 2, 6, 3, 6, 5),\n  Weight = c(100.5, 67.3, 80.4, 120.7, 54.2, 87.1, 70.8, 56.9, 56.6, 98.7)\n)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:21:40.712833Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:21:40.714510Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:21:40.731395Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:21:40.729578Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":42},{"cell_type":"code","source":"model <- lm(BMI ~ Age + Height + Weight, data = park)\nsummary(model)\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:21:17.998479Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:21:17.999788Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.019235Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.017529Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"\nCall:\nlm(formula = BMI ~ Age + Height + Weight, data = park)\n\nResiduals:\n    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max \n-29.222 -14.474  -5.849  19.342  31.250 \n\nCoefficients:\n            Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)   \n(Intercept) 154.1029    33.9164   4.544  0.00392 **\nAge           0.3368     0.2155   1.563  0.16907   \nHeight       -5.4154     6.5004  -0.833  0.43670   \nWeight       -0.4420     0.4722  -0.936  0.38545   \n---\nSignif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1\n\nResidual standard error: 26.37 on 6 degrees of freedom\nMultiple R-squared:  0.4645,\tAdjusted R-squared:  0.1968 \nF-statistic: 1.735 on 3 and 6 DF,  p-value: 0.2589\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":19},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Write a well commented program in R which import a .csv file from local disc C in a folder \nDATASCIENCE, subfolder EDA and file name DATA2025 and assign it to the object name SDS.      \nWrite an R command to  i)Attach the SDS  data and state the difference in importing specific data when \nthe data is not attached     ii)Calculate the average for the SDS data and write the formula    iii)Calculate the \nvariance and correlation for SDS data and write the formula   iv)If the data in SDS is quantitative display \nthe  bar plot and pie chart with back ground color, axis labels, title and labels**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"1. SDS <- read.csv(\"C:/DATASCIENCE/EDA/DATA2025.csv\")\nattach(SDS)\nWhen data is attached You can call columns directly by their name (e.g., 'Age').\nWhen data is not attached You must use the '$' operator\n\n\n3. Average\n   *  avg_sds <- mean(SDS$Variable_Name, na.rm = TRUE)\n Variance\n    * var_sds <- var(SDS$Variable_Name, na.rm = TRUE)\nCorrelation\n    * cor_sds <- cor(SDS$Variable1, SDS$Variable2, use = \"complete.obs\")\n\n      \n4. Visualization\n   barplot(SDS$Variable_Name, \n        col = \"blue\",          \n        main = \"SDS Quantitative Bar Plot\", \n        xlab = \"Observations\", \n        ylab = \"Values\")\n\n\npie(table(SDS$Variable_Name), \n    col = terrain.colors(5),      \n    main = \"SDS Quantitative Distribution\",\n    labels = names(table(SDS$Variable_Name)))\n\n\n    Code :\nSDS <- read.csv(\"C:/DATASCIENCE/EDA/DATA2025.csv\")\nattach(SDS)\n\navg_val <- mean(SDS$column_name, na.rm = TRUE)\nvar_val <- var(SDS$column_name)\ncor_val <- cor(SDS$col1, SDS$col2)\n\n\nbarplot(SDS$quant_col, col=\"blue\", main=\"Bar Plot\", xlab=\"X-Axis\", ylab=\"Y-Axis\")\npie(table(SDS$quant_col), col=rainbow(5), main=\"Pie Chart\")","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Give the general mathematical form of gamma distribution explaining all its parameters hence  \ngenerate 2000 random numbers from a gamma distribution, including   a code in R that gives its 99th \npercentile.  Hence Given the following elements 11,12,13,14 and 15,16,17,18  create  2*2 matrices  \nmaking them to be true by row hence  use normal mathematical procedures to find the inverse of the first \nmatrix hence write  R code that would give similar results including their matrix multiplication and their \nEigen values plus Eigen vectors.**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"* Gamma Distribution: Defined by shape ( alpha) and rate (Beta\n or scale (theta). Form: \n\nf(x;α,β)=(1/(Γ(α)βα1))^(xα−1e−x/β),x>0\n\n* α (shape parameter)\nControls the shape of the distribution\nSmall → highly skewed\nLarge → more symmetric\n* 𝛽\nβ (scale parameter)\nControls the spread (dispersion)\nLarger β → wider distribution\n* Γ(𝛼)\nΓ(α)\nGamma function (generalization of factorial)\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"set.seed(123)\n\n\nsamples <- rgamma(2000, shape = 2, scale = 3)\n\np99 <- quantile(samples, 0.99)\n\n\nhead(samples)\np99\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.021758Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.023257Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.051863Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-27T04:21:18.049850Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/html":"<style>\n.list-inline {list-style: none; margin:0; padding: 0}\n.list-inline>li {display: inline-block}\n.list-inline>li: